WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:17.928
Every other table shows you just one piece. Your odds,
your target, your stop. This one combines all of them into
a single question. For any target and stop you choose, do
you actually make money, or lose it? It's the whole trade,
in one grid.

2
00:00:18.528 --> 00:00:34.728
It's the EV Risk Matrix. EV means expected value, the
average dollars you'd make per trade over the long run.
Down the side are your possible profit targets. Across the
top are your possible stops. Every single cell is one
complete strategy. That target, paired with that stop.

3
00:00:35.328 --> 00:00:52.440
And the math inside each cell is simple and honest. How
often you hit the target, times what the target pays,
minus how often you get stopped, times what the stop
costs. Reward times its odds, minus risk times its odds.
That is expected value, the only number that survives a
thousand trades.

4
00:00:53.040 --> 00:01:12.120
Now the color does the work for you. Green cells make
money over time. Red cells lose money, no matter how good
they might feel in the moment. Look closely. Some of the
tight, high-probability targets are deep red, because
those small wins simply can't cover the losses. The best
green cells are where a realistic target meets a sensible
stop.

5
00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:26.592
So instead of guessing your target and your stop
separately, you read them together, right here. Find the
greenest cell you can realistically trade, and that pair,
that target and that stop, is your edge, proven in dollars
before you ever risk a cent.

6
00:01:27.192 --> 00:01:37.152
This grid is the strike rates, the risk ladder, and the
contract dollars, all multiplied together into the one
number that truly matters. Expected value per trade.

7
00:01:37.752 --> 00:01:43.152
Don't just pick a target. Don't just pick a stop. Pick the
green cell. The pair that actually pays.
